Interface ResultMapper<O>

  • Type Parameters:
    O -
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AverageMapMapper, CountDistinctMapMapper, CounterDistinctMapper, CounterMapper, DataObjectFactory.FilterAdapter, DataObjectFactory.ReferencedAdapter, DistinctMapper, ExistsMapper, GeneralMapMapper, LinkManager.JoinLinkMapper, MapMapper, MaximumDateMapMapper, MaximumMapMapper, MinimumDateMapMapper, MinimumMapMapper, RangeSearch.InfoMapper, ReductionMapper, SetMapper, SQLGroupMapper, SumMapMapper, TableMapper, TupleFactory.TupleMapper, ValueResultMapper

    public interface ResultMapper<O>
    Interface for classes that map ResultSets to Objects Where Filters are used to define which database records are to be selected a ResultMapper defines what data is to retrieved from these records and how it is to be converted into a domain object.

    • Method Detail

      • setQualify

        boolean setQualify(boolean qualify)
        Request that field names should be qualified with the table name where appropriate. This is for use with joined tables. For some result mappers this does not make sense so this method always returns the same value.
        Parameters:
        qualify -
        Returns:
        previous value of qualify flag

      • makeObject

        O makeObject(java.sql.ResultSet rs)
      throws DataException,
             java.sql.SQLException
        Convert a ResultSet into a domain object. The ResultSet should already be positioned at the correct starting Row to start creating the object It is legal for this method to return null to indicate the ResultSet represents an invalid record that should be ignored by the higher levels of the code.
        Parameters:
        rs - ResultSet or null
        Returns:
        domain object
        Throws:
        DataException
        java.sql.SQLException

      • makeDefault

        O makeDefault()
        Create a default Object to be returned if no SQL results are generated. If there is no obvious default result then return null. Where there is an obvious result (like a sum=0 or an empty Map) this is less error prone than trying to trap null at the calling level. Note that FilterFinder can optionally check for null results and generate exceptions this still fails but makes it easier to find the problem.
        Returns:
        domain object

      • getTarget

        java.lang.String getTarget()
        get the target clause of the SQL query. it makes sense to set it here as it has to match what the ResultMapper is expecting
        Returns:
        String
